{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17537419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17537419"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T17:17:30+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T17:17:30+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16025"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16025","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16025"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.68,0.09,0.08,0.07,0.08]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8716"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94679"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8716","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8716"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16025"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77712"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1061"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1356"},{"type":"tags","id":"1445"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4984"},{"type":"tags","id":"5820"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20847"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32486"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94679","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/94679"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a three-day history of high fevers, severe muscle aches, and headache. She returned from Bali one week ago and denies any unprotected sexual intercourse. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She did not have immunisations as a child due to her family beliefs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 100/70 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 38.9\u00b0C. There is a generalised blanching erythematous rash with scattered areas of normal skin. She has tender muscles and joints and small petechiae on her arms. There is no lymphadenopathy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaboratory investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPlatelet count: 95 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (150-400)\u003Cbr /\u003EWhite cell count: 2.8 \u00d7 10\u2079/L (4.0-11.0)\u003Cbr /\u003EHaemoglobin: 135 g/L (115-155)\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Dengue fever","Measles","Meningococcal disease","Zika virus infection","Chikungunya virus infection"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with the classic triad of fever, rash and myalgia following travel to an endemic area. The characteristic rash pattern of \u0027white islands in a sea of red\u0027, fever, along with thrombocytopenia and leucopenia, is highly suggestive of dengue fever. Dengue fever is caused by the dengue virus and is a notifiable disease to prevent localised outbreaks. It is carried by mosquitoes.  It is important to recognise as up to 1% of causes can be complicated by dengue haemorrhagic fever which has a 10 -20% mortality rate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDengue fever\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents 4-7 days after infection with fever, severe myalgia (\u0027breakbone fever\u0027), headache, and a characteristic rash which may be morbilliform, petechiae or mixed with dequamation of the skin. Laboratory findings often show thrombocytopenia and leucopenia in 25- 50% of cases which can lead to petechiae and bruising. The rash typically begins as a blanching erythema and evolves to show areas of normal skin creating the characteristic appearance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChikungunya virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E can present similarly with fever, rash and severe joint pains. However, the rash is typically maculopapular rather than showing the characteristic dengue pattern, and joint symptoms are typically more prominent than muscle pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeasles\u003C/strong\u003E presents with fever, cough, coryza, and conjunctivitis before the appearance of Koplik spots and a characteristic maculopapular rash that spreads from head to toe. Whilst it should be considered in an unvaccinated patient, the rash pattern and absence of respiratory symptoms make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeningococcal disease\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with a non-blanching purpuric rash and features of sepsis. While this patient has fever and appears unwell, her rash is blanching and she lacks other features of sepsis such as hypotension or altered mental status.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EZika virus infection\u003C/strong\u003E typically causes a milder illness with low-grade fever and a pruritic maculopapular rash. Joint pain is usually mild not severe, and severe myalgia is not a prominent feature.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The triad of severe fever, rash and myalgia is characteristic of dengue fever.","The typical rash in dengue fever begins as a blanching erythema and evolves into islands of sparing (\u0027white islands in a sea of red\u0027)."],"references":["Esler D.  Dengue: Clinical and Public Health Ramifications. Australian Family Physician. 2009: 38 (11).  Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/0cc0c5ba-f61e-4912-83ad-ff041b649a51/Dengue.aspx","Aryal E, Bista R, Shrestha PR, Regmi G. Dengue Fever among Patients Visiting the Outpatient Department of Dermatology in a Tertiary Care Centre: A Descriptive Cross-sectional Study. JNMA J Nepal Med Assoc. 2023.  Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10276932/","Adhikari S, Bhusal S, Hossain MS, et al. Assessment and management of dengue. BMJ 2025; 388:e082639"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77712"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16025"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"77712","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/77712"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-25T10:03:28+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-25T10:03:28+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8716"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"94679"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"